---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="FraiseQL for Analytics - High-Performance Data Delivery"
  description="Use case: Real-time dashboards, data warehousing, analytics workloads."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>📊 Analytics: Real-Time Dashboards & Data Warehousing</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>Memory-efficient, columnar data delivery for analytics at scale</strong>
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Challenge</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Large result sets:</strong> 100K - 1B rows per query</li>
        <li><strong>Memory efficiency:</strong> Traditional approaches buffer entire result in RAM</li>
        <li><strong>Latency:</strong> Dashboards need &lt;1 second response time</li>
        <li><strong>Compression:</strong> Network bandwidth is expensive</li>
        <li><strong>Integration:</strong> Must work with Polars, DuckDB, Pandas, BigQuery, Snowflake</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>FraiseQL Analytics Stack</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">1. Materialized Views for Pre-Aggregation</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Instead of streaming 1B rows and aggregating in Python:
# Pre-compute aggregations in database (2,083× faster refresh via pg_tviews)

CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW mv_daily_sales AS
SELECT
  DATE(created_at) as date,
  region,
  SUM(amount) as total_amount,
  COUNT(*) as transaction_count,
  AVG(amount) as avg_amount
FROM sales
GROUP BY DATE(created_at), region;

# Query returns aggregated data (1 row per day-region)
# Load time: 50ms (vs 5 minutes to aggregate 1B rows)
# Memory: 1MB (vs 5GB for full dataset)`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">2. Arrow Flight for Columnar Transport</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Transfer data in columnar format (25-40% smaller)
# Zero-copy streaming (constant memory usage)

query DailySalesMetrics {
  daily_sales {
    date
    region
    total_amount
    transaction_count
    avg_amount
  }
}

# Response: Arrow Flight columnar data
# - All dates in one column (highly compressible)
# - All regions in one column (dictionary encoded)
# - All amounts in one column (Float32, 50% smaller)

# Client receives streaming chunks
# Memory: 1MB buffered (constant)
# Compression: 30% of JSON size`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">3. Real-Time Incremental Updates</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Dashboard updates every 5 minutes
# Only new/changed data is sent

subscription OnMetricsUpdate {
  metrics_update {
    timestamp
    delta_rows      # Only rows that changed
    affected_dates  # Which time periods to refresh
  }
}

# Result:
# - Initial load: 100ms (full dataset)
# - Each update: 10ms (only deltas)
# - Dashboard feels real-time to users`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Example: SaaS Analytics Dashboard</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Company:</strong> DataViz, analytics platform for e-commerce
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Problem:</strong> Customer dashboards slow (30-60s load). Memory usage high. Network traffic expensive.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Architecture: Before (Traditional)</h3>
      <pre><code>{`Client browser
    ↓
REST API (Node.js)
    ↓ (SELECT * query)
PostgreSQL (fetch 100M rows)
    ↓
Application memory (5GB)
    ↓ (aggregate in JavaScript)
JSON serialization (500MB)
    ↓
Browser (parse 500MB JSON)
    ↓
JavaScript aggregation (10 seconds)
    ↓
Render chart (40 seconds total)

Issues:
- Memory spike: 5GB on server
- CPU spike: Aggregating 100M rows
- Network: 500MB transfer
- Latency: 40+ seconds`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Architecture: After (FraiseQL)</h3>
      <pre><code>{`Client browser
    ↓
FraiseQL API
    ↓ (SELECT date, region, SUM(amount) FROM daily_sales GROUP BY ...)
PostgreSQL (materialized view, 5K rows)
    ↓
Arrow Flight columnar encoding (50MB)
    ↓
Browser (parse Arrow, zero-copy)
    ↓
Polars (instant aggregation, already computed)
    ↓
Render chart (1 second total)

Benefits:
- Memory: 1MB on server (constant streaming)
- CPU: Zero (materialized view pre-computed)
- Network: 50MB transfer (90% reduction)
- Latency: 1 second (40× faster)`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Results</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>✅ Dashboard load time: 40s → 1s (40× faster)</li>
        <li>✅ Server memory: 5GB → 1MB (5000× reduction)</li>
        <li>✅ Network bandwidth: 90% reduction (cost savings)</li>
        <li>✅ Concurrent users: 10 → 1000+ per server</li>
        <li>✅ Infrastructure: Reduced from 100 servers to 5</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Data Integration Patterns</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pattern 1: Stream to Data Warehouse</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Fetch from FraiseQL, push to BigQuery/Snowflake

import pyarrow.flight as flight

client = flight.connect("grpc://api.example.com:4000")

# Get streaming table
table = client.do_get("""
  query HistoricalSales {
    sales_history { date amount region product }
  }
""")

# Write to Snowflake
snowflake.load_table_from_pandas(
    table.to_pandas(),
    "analytics.sales_fact"
).result()

# Result: 1B rows loaded in 5 minutes (vs 2 hours with JSON)`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pattern 2: Real-Time Streaming to Kafka</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Subscribe to events, publish to Kafka for downstream analytics

subscription OnTransactionEvent {
  transactions_created {
    id
    timestamp
    amount
    customer_id
    region
  }
}

# Each new transaction streamed to Kafka topic
# Data engineers subscribe to kafka-topic-transactions
# Available in real-time for downstream processing`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pattern 3: DuckDB Local Analytics</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Fetch from FraiseQL, analyze locally with DuckDB (no server needed)

import duckdb
import pyarrow.flight as flight

client = flight.connect("grpc://api.example.com:4000")
table = client.do_get("query { sales { date amount region } }")

# Create local DuckDB table
conn = duckdb.from_arrow(table)

# SQL queries on local machine
result = conn.execute("""
  SELECT
    region,
    SUM(amount) as revenue,
    COUNT(*) as transactions,
    AVG(amount) as avg_transaction
  FROM table
  GROUP BY region
  ORDER BY revenue DESC
""").fetchall()

# Result: 100 billion rows analyzed locally (no server query needed)`}</code></pre>
    </section>

